<h2>Therapy Is Participatory</h2>
<p>Therapy is not done to you — it's done with you. The client's active engagement is consistently one of the strongest predictors of outcomes. People who think about sessions between appointments, attempt between-session practices, and bring real, current concerns — not just what feels "appropriate" to discuss — consistently do better.</p>

<p>There is no right way to do therapy. But there are practices that consistently get people more from it.</p>

<h2>Before the Session</h2>
<p><strong>Know what you want to bring.</strong> You don't need a formal agenda, but having some sense of what's been on your mind — what happened this week, what pattern has been troubling you, what you want to understand better — helps use session time well. Jotting notes between sessions when something significant happens is useful.</p>

<p><strong>Think about what you've been avoiding.</strong> The topics that feel too uncomfortable, embarrassing, or "silly" to bring up are often the most important. Avoidance in life tends to replicate in therapy if you let it.</p>

<h2>In the Session</h2>

<p><strong>Say what's actually going on.</strong> Not the polished, coherent version — the real version, including confusion, contradiction, and difficulty articulating things. Therapists are trained to work with uncertainty and complexity; you don't need to have it figured out before you say it.</p>

<p><strong>Tell them when something doesn't land.</strong> If an interpretation doesn't fit, if a suggestion feels wrong, if you felt dismissed — say so. This is some of the most valuable material in therapy. Therapists are not infallible, and the process of working through disagreement is itself therapeutically productive.</p>

<p><strong>Notice what happens in your body.</strong> Strong emotional responses — tightening in the chest, a sudden shift in mood, urge to change the subject — are information. Mentioning them ("I notice I suddenly feel anxious when I talk about this") gives the therapist useful material.</p>

<p><strong>Bring the relationship into the room.</strong> How you feel about your therapist, reactions you have to things they say or do — these often mirror relational patterns from outside the therapy room. A good therapist will welcome this rather than finding it intrusive.</p>

<h2>Between Sessions</h2>
<p>What happens between sessions matters as much as what happens in them. If your therapist suggests between-session practices — behavioural activation, journaling, exposure exercises — take them seriously. They're not optional extras; they're how change transfers from the therapy room to life.</p>

<p>When you notice something significant between sessions — a dream, a strong reaction, a moment of clarity or confusion — write it down. Bring it to the next session.</p>

<h2>When to Raise Concerns</h2>
<p>If therapy isn't feeling productive, say so — in the session. "I feel like we're going around the same ground without things shifting" is useful feedback, not criticism. Most good therapists will welcome it and adjust. If progress continues to stall after raising concerns, the therapist isn't right for you and it's reasonable to seek someone else.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>What if I cry or get very emotional?</strong><br/>
This is entirely expected and often a sign that important material is being touched. A therapist has seen every range of emotional expression and will not be alarmed. Emotional engagement in sessions is associated with better outcomes, not with being "too much."</p>

<p><strong>Can I ask my therapist questions about their approach?</strong><br/>
Yes. You can and should feel able to ask what approach they're taking, why they suggested something, or what they make of a pattern they've noticed. Transparency is appropriate and legitimate to ask for.</p>

<p><strong>What if I have nothing to say?</strong><br/>
This happens. Saying "I don't know where to start" or "I'm feeling blank today" is fine to say. The emptiness can itself be worked with. You're not obligated to perform engagement when it isn't there.</p>

